"Post E., Forchhammer M.C.","Climate change reduces reproductive success of an Arctic herbivore through trophic mismatch",2008,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","363","1501",,"2369","2375",,,10.1098/rstb.2007.2207,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-44449111215&partnerID=40&md5=daf992974a11681e864fa1949aa44675","Department of Biology, Penn State University, 208 Mueller Lab., University Park, PA 16802, United States; Department of Arctic Environment, National Environmental Research Institute, University of Aarhus, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; Centre for Integrated Population Ecology","Post, E., Department of Biology, Penn State University, 208 Mueller Lab., University Park, PA 16802, United States, Department of Arctic Environment, National Environmental Research Institute, University of Aarhus, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark; Forchhammer, M.C., Department of Arctic Environment, National Environmental Research Institute, University of Aarhus, Frederiksborgvej 399, 4000 Roskilde, Denmark, Centre for Integrated Population Ecology","In highly seasonal environments, offspring production by vertebrates is timed to coincide with the annual peak of resource availability. For herbivores, this resource peak is represented by the annual onset and progression of the plant growth season. As plant phenology advances in response to climatic warming, there is potential for development of a mismatch between the peak of resource demands by reproducing herbivores and the peak of resource availability. For migratory herbivores, such as caribou, development of a trophic mismatch is particularly likely because the timing of their seasonal migration to summer ranges, where calves are born, is cued by changes in day length, while onset of the plant-growing season on the same ranges is cued by local temperatures. Using data collected since 1993 on timing of calving by caribou and timing of plant growth in West Greenland, we document the consequences for reproductive success of a developing trophic mismatch between caribou and their forage plants. As mean spring temperatures at our study site have risen by more than 4°C, caribou have not kept pace with advancement of the plant-growing season on their calving range. As a consequence, offspring mortality has risen and offspring production has dropped fourfold. © 2007 The Royal Society.","Caribou; Climate change; Global warming; Plant phenology","climate change; deer; global warming; herbivore; phenology; reproduction; reproductive success; resource availability; trophic structure; animal; article; comparative study; fertility; food chain; greenhouse effect; Greenland; growth, development and aging; physiology; plant; population dynamics; reindeer; season; temperature; Animals; Fertility; Food Chain; Greenhouse Effect; Greenland; Plants; Population Dynamics; Reindeer; Seasons; Temperature; Arctic; Greenland; West Greenland; Rangifer tarandus; Vertebrata",,,,,,"Adams, L.G., Singer, F.J., Dale, B.W., Caribou calf mortality in Denali National Park (1995) J. Wildl. Manage, 59, pp. 584-594; Albon, S.D., Langvatn, R., Plant phenology and the benefits of migration in a temperate ungulate (1992) Oikos, 65, pp. 502-513. , doi:10.2307/3545568; Both, C., Visser, M., Adjustment to climate change is constrained by arrival date in a long-distance migrant bird (2001) Nature, 411, pp. 296-298. , doi:10.2307/3545568; Both, C., Bouwhuis, S., Lessells, C.M., Visser, M., Climate change and population declines in a long-distance migratory bird (2006) Nature, 441, pp. 81-83. , doi:10.2307/3545568; Bøving, P.S., Post, E., Vigilance and foraging behaviour of female caribou in relation to predation risk (1997) Rangifer, 17, pp. 55-63. , doi:10.2307/3545568; Caughley, G., (1977) Analysis of vertebrate populations, , London, UK: Wiley; Caughley, G., Caughley, J., Estimating median date of birth (1974) J. Wildl. Manage, 38, pp. 552-556. , doi:10.23